    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-10-06T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-10-06T14:00:00-05:00" n="229"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d229">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A4 Steering Committee/80: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The American Delegate (<persName corresp="#p_WHR1" type="from"
                            >Wilson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-10-06T20:00:00+01:00"
                            >October 6, 1932—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received October 6—5:08 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>402. In the first general discussion of the Committee for the Regulation of Trade
                    in and Manufacture of Arms this afternoon <persName corresp="#p_JL1"
                        >Jouhaux</persName>, France, made appeal for the total abolition of private
                    manufacture of arms and munitions of war. If this is not possible he then
                    recommended the establishment of a strict control and restriction of
                    production.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_MSD1">Madariaga</persName> emphasized the importance of
                    establishing the same system for private and state manufacture and desired to
                    apply a tripartite system providing for control of both private and state
                    manufacture, control of surplus on hand and a more adequate control of arms
                    traffic which would be brought about through the deposit of copies of all
                    licenses for both import and export shipments of arms with a central control
                    office in Geneva.</p>
                <p>During the general discussion which followed I summarized the American position
                    both as regard our constitutional difficulty and as regard full publicity for
                    both private and state manufacture and expressed the thought that possibly
                        <persName corresp="#p_MSD1">Madariaga</persName>’s suggestion of a deposit
                    of licenses of arms shipments with a disarmament commission in Geneva should be
                    carefully considered since it might provide the means of conciliating the
                    different points of view and provide a solution.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_WHR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
